# Safe Process Killing for TaskGo

## The Problem (root cause identified)

`pkill -f "TaskGo!"` matches the FULL command line of ALL processes. Cursor's own extension-host processes contain the workspace name "TaskGo!" in their arguments:

- `Cursor Helper (Plugin): extension-host (retrieval-always-local) TaskGo!`
- `Cursor Helper (Plugin): extension-host (agent-exec) TaskGo!`
- `Cursor Helper (Plugin): extension-host (user) TaskGo!`

So `pkill -f "TaskGo!"` kills Cursor itself, causing it to freeze and become unresponsive.

## The Fix

Always use the full binary path pattern to target ONLY the app:

```bash
# SAFE — targets only the actual app binary
pkill -f 'TaskGo!.app/Contents/MacOS/TaskGo!' 2>/dev/null

# DANGEROUS — kills Cursor's own processes too, NEVER use this
pkill -f "TaskGo!" 2>/dev/null
```

## Rules

1. When killing the TaskGo app, ALWAYS match against `TaskGo!.app/Contents/MacOS/TaskGo!`
2. NEVER use a bare `pkill -f "TaskGo!"` — it will kill Cursor
3. `sleep` commands are fine to use when needed
4. `pkill` and `kill` are fine to use as long as they target the right process
